This seems to be a tricky one and my explanation would be following:

The `FiendsList` entity has a composite primary key which consists of `userId` and `friendId` column. Both of them reference the `User.userId` column:

        @JoinColumn(name = &quot;userid&quot;, referencedColumnName = &quot;userid&quot;)
        public Long getUserId(){
             return this.userId;
        }

        @JoinColumn(name = &quot;friendid&quot;, referencedColumnName = &quot;userid&quot;)
        public Long getFriendId(){
             return this.friendId;
        }

On the User entity however you only put the mapping to the `FiendList.user` field:

    @OneToMany(mappedBy = &quot;user&quot;, fetch = FetchType.EAGER, cascade = CascadeType.ALL)
    public Set&lt;FriendsList&gt; getFriendsList() {
        return this.friendsList;
    }

The thing is that is not enough for hibernate to know what to do as it needs two column in order to properly fetch the FriendsList entity (as it has composite pk).

You may need to perform an additional query once you get the User entity in order to get the `FriendList` by passing the retrieved `User.userId` value as part of the `FriendListPk`:

    @Repository
    public interface FriendListDao extends JpaRepository&lt;FriendList, FriendListPK&gt;{
        ... // use one of the find methods to get by pk.
    }

Oops, silly me, turns out I was just missing an &quot;s&quot; in the setter.

    public void setFriendsList(Set&lt;FriendsList&gt; friendList) {
        this.friendsList = friendsList;
    }


the &quot;friendlist&quot; argurment should in fact be &quot;friendslist&quot;.  Hibernate was fetching the data, but when it tried to assign it to the field, the existing instance variable was silently being assigned to itself rather than the argument of the setter.

